observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE):
Fast-track or expedite the creation of a functional Inventory Committee. Mobilize additional competent personnel from other departments to assist and facilitate the completion of the physical count of all PPE items;
Instruct the Inventory Committee to undertake physical inventory of all the PPE items to determine their physical existence, location, condition and other relevant information, and immediately prepare the corresponding RPCPPE;
Require the MAO to maintain complete and updated PPELCs to support GL account balances and the Supply Officer to keep corresponding PCs for control purposes;
Strengthen accounting controls of PPE accounts by performing periodic reconciliation of records, and ensure that discrepancies are immediately investigated and adjusted in the books; and
Avail the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts provided under COA Circular No. 2020-006 relative to the conduct of physical count of PPE, recognition of PPE items found at station, and disposition for non-existing/missing PPE items.

We recommended that the LCE require the:
MAO, MGSO and the MEO to prepare and submit the necessary reports and records pertaining to local road network in accordance with the prescribed formats as provided under COA Circular No. 2015-008;
MA and the GSO to conduct regular reconciliation of LRNLCs and the LRNPCs at least on quarterly basis;
Municipal Engineer to furnish the MA and the GSO with complete description and cost segregation of the various road components for completed road projects as basis for recording in their respective records; and
MA to disclose the total road network in the Notes to the FS as per Annex B of the aforesaid circular.

We recommended that the LCE:
Instruct the MA and the MT to conduct monthly/quarterly/yearly reconciliation of their cash records and maintain a reconciliation report at year-end to avoid discrepancies;
Direct the MA to exert extra efforts and obtain the necessary documents needed to support the identified reconciling items and draw Journal Entry Vouchers (JEV) to record all valid reconciling items that require adjustment/correction in the book.  Otherwise, open new bank account and disclose in the Notes to FS the noted reconciling items;
Require the MA to drop from the book of accounts the identified non-existing bank account; and
Instruct the MA to communicate immediately to the concerned AGDBs any errors committed by the bank which were identified during the preparation of the BRS for correction.

Instruct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to prioritize the reconciliation of the Cash in Bank accounts in order to come up with the correct balance of the said accounts to be presented in the FS;

Exert extra effort and obtain all the necessary documents needed to support the identified reconciling items and draw Journal Entry Vouchers (JEV) to record all valid reconciling items that require adjustment/correction in the book;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to conduct a thorough review of records to determine the validity of long outstanding deposits in transit and make the necessary adjustments; and

Ensure that any errors committed by the bank which were identified during the preparation of the BRS be immediately communicated to the concerned depository bank for correction.

The VM and Members of the SB immediately stop the practice of granting assistance to their constituents charge against respective funds as this is not among their mandated duties and functions under Sections 445 and 447 of RA No. 7160;

Management see to it that the applicable laws, rules and regulations, particularly Sections 2 and 4 (1) of PD No. 1445 are observed in the disbursement of public funds; and 

Expenses are properly classified according to their respective account name and description to properly present the same in the financial statements.

Require the Municipal Accountant to exert effort to properly identify the sources and status of implementation of the funds transferred by NGAs and prepare a comprehensive schedule for the same; 

Make a representation or confirm from the SAs as to whether or not the balance of the funds transferred to the Municipality with completed PPAs should be returned or be utilized by the LGU; and

Return the said unutilized funds to the Bureau of National Treasury, if the documents or records of the specific accounts cannot be located or trace anymore.

Strictly monitor the conduct of regular and periodic verification, analysis and validation of the existence of receivable and payable accounts to ensure that only valid receivables and payables are recorded in the books; 

Prepare a detailed schedule and ageing of receivables and payables once valid supporting documents are retrieved; 

Document and file a request for authority to write-off dormant receivable accounts to COA as prescribed by the above cited Circular. Pending approval of such write-off, disclosed the actual account status in the Notes to FS to fairly present the receivable accounts in the FS;

Prepare a certified schedule of ageing of dormant payable accounts for which there are no valid claimants/creditors and no supporting documents, and thereafter; 

Revert the verified amounts to the Unappropriated Surplus of the Government Equity Account by preparing the necessary Journal Entry Vouchers as basis for recording in the books of accounts of the Municipality; and

As regards to the Trust Fund accounts, confirm the balances with the SA and return any unutilized balances due to them.

We recommended that Management direct the Municipal Accountant to:

Exert effort to trace and analyze the pertinent transactions in order to reconcile the difference of ₱0.77 million in the reciprocal accounts Due from/Due to Other Funds; 

Thereafter, prepare the necessary adjusting entries to reflect the correct balances of the subject accounts;

Ensure that the discrepancy between the reciprocal accounts be immediately eliminated, if not, reduce the balance of said amount in the ensuing year; and

Conduct periodic reconciliation of the reciprocal accounts in order to identify possible errors/adjustments which need to be adjusted in the books.

Prepare a three-year program indicating strategic prioritization policies in the allocation of the SEF to schools; 

Gather and keep records of the information needed to be considered in the planning and budgeting for SEF, particularly the SIP and DEDP; 

Consolidate the project proposals prepared and submitted by the School Heads for their respective SEF allocation which shall form part of the documentary support for the approval of the SEF Budget;
 Ensure that the proposed PPAs presented in the SEF Budget are specifically identified as to name of the project, program and activity, allotment class and recipient school; and 

Observe fully the policies in the planning and budgeting for SEF and the procedures and timelines in the preparation and approval of the budget for the said fund as stated in the DepEd, DBM and DILG JC No. 01, series of 2017.

Conduct a detailed review and analysis of the Inter-Agency Payables accounts, including confirmation and reconciliation with the concerned government agencies in order to come up with the correct unremitted balances of the subject accounts. Thereafter, prepare the necessary adjusting entry, if any; 

Closely monitor the preparation of the needed schedules for the remittance of the withheld amounts and ensure its remittance in full within the prescribed deadlines; and 

Remit immediately the monthly withheld contributions to BIR, GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth to avoid paying penalties, surcharges and interest arising from delayed remittances.

Secure a certification on the balances and status from the concerned depository bank on the balances of the bank account number 5325-645-7 maintained in the Development Bank of the Philippines (DBP) and bank account number 0782-1066-43 maintained in the Land Bank of the Philippines (LBP). Thereafter, take the necessary appropriate action in order to update the records of the Municipality;

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to exert extra effort in locating the documents relative to prior years reconciling items and ensure that book reconciling items will not increase in the succeeding years; and

Communicate to the concerned depository bank regarding the bank errors presented in the BRS in order to arrive at the correct balance of the CIB-LCCA.

Require the Municipal Accountant to meticulously verify the status of long outstanding fund transfers/payables still maintained in its books and adhere to the provisions cited by Section 111 of PD No. 1445; 

Require the Municipal Treasurer to issue confirmation of payables to the payor/trustor/grantor to verify the existence of liabilities and if validated pay and/or remit to the grantor-agency/payor any unutilized amount/unpaid payables pursuant to their existing contract; and

Request for write-off of long outstanding accounts or dormant accounts or reversion of payable as provided by COA Circulars No.  99-004, 93-404 and 2015-001.

We recommended that Management:

Secure copies of the Torrens Title of its lots drawn in the name of the Municipality from the Land Registration Authority;


Allocate budget for the cost of processing and securing Torrens Title for the untitled land.

