We recommended that Management:

Instruct the concerned personnel to conduct proper and thorough evaluation and inspection of mini dump trucks that are fully depreciated to determine whether the repair would still be viable and economical;

Consider the disposal of the aging trucks or vehicles and consider the acquisition of new ones to avoid the incurrence of unnecessary repairs;




Trace the source documents relevant to the unrecorded dump truck and make the necessary adjustments in the books;




Ensure that all disbursement vouchers be supported with complete documentation and submit within the prescribed period to facilitate the review of the transactions; and 

Properly identify in the supporting documents the vehicle or truck that are subjected to repair.

We recommended that Management:

Prioritize the updating of RPT records by providing enough manpower and equipment to the MTO so that said Office will be able to prepare all the needed reports for the establishment and collection of RPT and  SET Receivables;

Prepare a complete certified list of taxpayers based on RPT Account Register/Taxpayer’s index card so as to provide correct basis in setting up of the RPT/SET Receivables;

Post the list of taxpayers with unpaid taxes in the conspicuous places within the Municipality including its component barangays; and 

Seek the aid of the barangay officials in the collection of RPT/SET by informing the taxpayers in each barangay of their responsibility of paying the tax.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Instruct the concerned personnel to conduct proper and thorough evaluation and inspection of mini dump trucks that are fully depreciated to determine whether the repair would still be viable and economical;
Consider the disposal of the aging trucks or vehicles and consider the acquisition of new ones to avoid the incurrence of unnecessary repairs;
Trace the source documents relevant to the unrecorded dump truck and make the necessary adjustments in the books;
Ensure that all disbursement vouchers be supported with complete documentation and submit within the prescribed period to facilitate the review of the transactions; and
Properly identify in the supporting documents the vehicle or truck that are subjected to repair.

In view of the above conditions, we recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:

Prepare and submit timely the BRS pursuant to Section 3.2 of COA Circular No. 96-011 to provide the Audit Team enough time to examine the said documents;

Conduct a thorough review of records to determine the validity of all reconciling items and come up with the correct balance of Cash in Bank accounts;

Properly notify the depository banks of those items that need adjustments within 10 days upon receipt of the bank statement to immediately address the cause/s of the discrepancy between the cash balances per bank and per books and accordingly effect adjustment to eliminate errors; and

Exhaust all possible actions in order to perform the reconciliations.

We recommended that Management: 

Require the BAC, the Secretariat and the TWG to strictly abide by the standards set forth by RA No. 9184, its Revised IRR and other relevant laws on government procurement;  

Require them also to exercise due diligence in the performance of their duties to ensure that all requirements of the procurement law are faithfully adhered to; 

Direct the Municipal Accountant to observe the requirements of COA Circular No. 2012-001 at all times to avoid suspension or disallowance in audit; and

Submit the original supporting documents for the payments of the rescue vehicles.
